# Mega-Section UI Standard

Use this standard for all large page surfaces across renderer (`timer`, `stats`, `ranks`, `home`, `rituals`, `calendar`, `diary`, `settings`, and future dashboard-like pages).

- Use one monolithic shell only: `PageFrame` -> one `Card` -> one `CardContent`.
- Reuse shared layout tokens from `renderer/src/shared/ui/mega-section-layout.ts`.
- Keep page structure stable: `min-h-0`, `min-w-0`, `flex-1`, `overflow-hidden` on every parent layer.
- Prefer parent `divide-x` / `divide-y` for panel separation; avoid nested card-in-card wrappers.
- Use unified panel header style (`MEGA_PANEL_HEADER_CN`) with micro title (`MEGA_PANEL_MICRO_TITLE_CN`).
- Use unified scroll body style (`MEGA_PANEL_BODY_CN`) and keep scroll at leaf panels.
- Keep titles short and functional; avoid duplicated subtitles/date badges when context already provides it.
- Keep list and checklist rows single-line by default; do not render secondary subtitle lines in standard section lists.
- Keep spacing compact and consistent across panels (`p-2.5..p-4` range).
- Numeric/meta text should use mono/tabular where applicable.

## Do Not

- Do not create multi-level card nesting for major page sections.
- Do not mix unrelated header heights or ad-hoc title typography in mega-sections.
- Do not add decorative-only wrappers that reduce usable vertical space.
- Do not introduce local one-off shell classes if shared tokens already cover the pattern.

## Audit Checklist

- Shell layout uses `PageFrame` + `MEGA_PAGEFRAME_CONTENT_CN` + `MEGA_SHELL_CARD_CN` + `MEGA_SHELL_CONTENT_CN`.
- Panel split uses only parent `divide-*`; no duplicated `border-*` on adjacent children that create double lines.
- Panel headers use `MegaPanelHeader` or `MEGA_PANEL_HEADER_CN` with consistent height and paddings.
- Leaf panel content uses `MEGA_PANEL_BODY_CN` (or compact equivalent inside this range) and keeps scroll at leaf level.
- List/check rows in section bodies are single-line unless explicitly using the dedicated diary row mode.
- Section spacing remains in compact range and avoids ad-hoc large gaps for core surfaces.
